== Notable Kofun == * [[:en:Kamegamori-Chinjumori Kofun|Kamegamori-Chinjumori Kofun]] - A National Historic Site. Kamegamori Kofun, at 127 meters in length, is the largest in the prefecture. * {{ill|Kinegamori Kofun|ja|杵ガ森古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kinegamori Kofun|qq=}} - Among the oldest kofun in the Tohoku region, constructed in the early 4th century. * Usagamori Kofun * Nagaimae no Yama Kofun - Features a gabled ceiling stone coffin, constructed in the early 5th century. * Kokuzomori Kofun * Tenjinmen Kofun * {{ill|Hazukayama Kofun|lt=Hazukayama Kofun|lt=Haizukayama Kofun|ja|灰塚山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haizukayama Kofun|qq=}} * Miyahigashi No. 1 Kofun * Raijinzan No. 1 Kofun * Morikita No. 1 Kofun * Kajiyama No. 4 Kofun * Dezakiyama No. 1 Kofun * Dezakiyama No. 2 Kofun * Dezakiyama No. 3 Kofun * Dezakiyama No. 4 Kofun
Additionally, it is said that a kofun called Maigamori Kofun existed between Kinegamori and Usagamori Kofun.
== References == * Hidehito Tsuji, *The Foundation of Tohoku Kofun Research: Aizu Otsukayama Kofun*, "Learning from Historical Sites" Series 029, Shinseisha, 2006. == See Also == * {{ill|List of Kofun in Japan|ja|日本の古墳一覧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/List of Kofun in Japan|qq=}}
